"""
MKT Context Commentary — Hebrews chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hebrews-1-5.py

Key decisions:
- Audience: likely Jewish Christians in Rome (or Jerusalem) facing pressure to return to Judaism
- Angelology: Second Temple Jewish angel traditions (1 Enoch, Qumran, Philo)
- 2:2 mediated law: tradition that Torah was given through angels (Gal 3:19; Acts 7:53; Josephus, Ant. 15.136)
- 2:14-15 fear of death: Epicurean fear-of-death discussions vs. Jewish afterlife hope
- 3:1-6 Moses comparison: Moses as the supreme mediator of Second Temple Judaism
- 4:14-16 high priest: Hasmonean and Herodian period's compromised high priesthood as foil
- 5:11-14 milk vs. solid food: Greek philosophical pedagogical categories
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HEBREWS = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>The opening of Hebrews exhibits the rhetorical style of a polished homily — its Greek has been called the most literary in the NT (Thyen, Attridge). The prologue\'s structure reflects the Hellenistic rhetorical practice of the <em>exordium</em> (introduction that establishes the speaker\'s ethos and frames the argument). The contrast between God\'s multiple-mode speaking through the prophets and the singular speaking through the Son reflects the Jewish theology of prophetic revelation developed in Philo (On the Migration of Abraham 34-35) and the rabbinic discussion of progressive divine self-disclosure. The prologue presupposes a Jewish-Christian community that honors the prophets as divine speakers and needs to hear the argument that the Son\'s speech exceeds rather than contradicts them.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The Son as agent of creation picks up the Jewish Wisdom tradition that personified divine Wisdom as God\'s agent in creation (Prov 8:22-31; Wis 7:22-8:1; Sir 24). Philo of Alexandria identified the divine Logos (Word/Reason) with the instrument of creation (On the Creation of the World 20-25). Hebrews does not use "Wisdom" or "Logos" directly but inherits the same conceptual framework: the pre-existent mediator of creation who is now the final mediator of revelation. The combination of creation-agency with inheritance-appointment reflects the royal theology of Ps 2, where the king both builds and inherits God\'s household.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The superiority-to-angels argument was not chosen arbitrarily. In Second Temple Judaism, angels held an elevated status as divine intermediaries. 1 Enoch 70-71 portrays Enoch/Metatron as a transformed human who joins the angelic company; Qumran\'s Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice (4Q400-407) describes the angelic liturgy in the heavenly sanctuary; the Dead Sea Scrolls community understood themselves as worshiping alongside the angels. In this environment, proving the Son\'s superiority to angels was substantive: some Jewish traditions placed the Torah-giving angel (identified in Gal 3:19 and Acts 7:53 as the mediator of the Mosaic law) very high. The argument that the Son exceeds even the most elevated mediator is the theological foundation for the entire letter\'s claim.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Psalm 2 was an explicitly messianic text in Second Temple Judaism. 4Q174 (Florilegium) from Qumran interprets Ps 2:7 and 2 Sam 7:14 together as referring to the Branch of David who will arise in the last days — exactly the combination Hebrews 1:5 makes. The Messianic Apocalypse (4Q521) describes a figure whom heaven and earth will obey. Psalms of Solomon 17 describes the Son of David who will be called Lord of the kingdom. Hebrews draws on a widely shared messianic interpretation of these texts while applying them specifically to Jesus\'s resurrection-exaltation rather than to a future figure.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The characterization of angels as "ministering spirits" (<em>leitourgika pneumata</em>) reflects the Jewish liturgical understanding of the angelic host as the heavenly worship-assembly. The Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice from Qumran describes the angels as the priests of the heavenly sanctuary who offer praise to God. 1 Enoch 40 identifies four archangels with specific ministering roles. The Jewish synagogue liturgy included the <em>Kedushah</em> (sanctification) prayer based on the angelic "Holy, holy, holy" of Isa 6:3, situating earthly worship in participation with the angelic host. Hebrews\' point is that the Son is over this entire angelic ministering-system, not part of it.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "2": '<p>"The word declared by angels" — the tradition that the Torah was mediated through angelic intermediaries at Sinai is attested in multiple first-century sources: Josephus (Antiquities 15.136), Philo (On Dreams 1.141-143), Galatians 3:19 ("ordained through angels by an intermediary"), Acts 7:53 ("you who received the law as delivered by angels"), and the LXX of Deuteronomy 33:2 (which mentions "angels" alongside the Sinai theophany). The Book of Jubilees explicitly names the "Angel of the Presence" as the one who dictated the Torah to Moses. This tradition elevated the Torah\'s authority by associating it with angelic intermediaries; Hebrews acknowledges the tradition ("if the word declared by angels proved to be reliable") before claiming the Son\'s word is greater.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Psalm 8\'s "son of man" and "son of Adam" language intersects with the Jewish "Son of Man" traditions of Daniel 7:13-14 and 1 Enoch\'s Parables (chs. 37-71), where the Son of Man is an eschatological figure of divine authority. Hebrews 2:6-9 reads Ps 8 as describing this trajectory: the human figure who is humiliated and then exalted to dominion. The phrase "made a little lower than the angels" (Ps 8:5, <em>par\' angelous</em> in LXX) had created interpretive interest — was this the human creature generally, or a specific exalted human figure? Hebrews resolves the question by applying it to the incarnate Son\'s humiliation-exaltation pattern.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"The power of death, that is, the devil" — the identification of the devil with death\'s power reflects Second Temple Jewish demonology. Wisdom of Solomon 2:24 states "through the devil\'s envy death entered the world" — the interpretation that Satan introduced death into creation through the Eden deception. 1 Enoch 9:1 and multiple Qumran texts (the War Scroll, 1QM) describe the cosmic combat between the Prince of Light and the Prince of Darkness (Belial). The fear of death that Hebrews 2:15 identifies as the enslaving mechanism was also a major topic in Hellenistic philosophy: Epicurus taught that the fear of death was the primary source of human anxiety, and his philosophy aimed to liberate people from it. Hebrews addresses the same fear but through Christ\'s death-destroying death rather than through philosophical persuasion.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The Aaronic high priesthood\'s structure and significance would have been intimately familiar to the Jewish community Hebrews addresses. The high priest\'s office in first-century Judaism was a politically charged institution: the Hasmoneans (140-63 BCE) had combined the high priesthood with the kingship, a combination many regarded as improper. Herod the Great and his successors appointed and dismissed high priests as political tools — between Herod\'s reign and the destruction of the Temple (37 BCE - 70 CE), there were 28 different high priests. The Qumran community rejected the Jerusalem high priesthood entirely, preferring the memory of the Zadokite lineage. Hebrews\' claim that Jesus is the true high priest engages this contested institution at its most theologically sensitive point.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>Moses held an unparalleled place in Second Temple Jewish piety. Philo of Alexandria wrote multiple treatises devoted to Moses (On the Life of Moses, 2 volumes) in which he portrays Moses as the ideal philosopher-king, the divine legislator, the prophet who spoke face-to-face with God. The rabbis would later say "from Moses to Moses, there arose none like Moses" (comparing Moses of the Torah with Moses Maimonides). The Dead Sea Scrolls quote Moses with reverence throughout; the Damascus Document and the Temple Scroll present Moses as the supreme interpreter of God\'s will. For Hebrews\' audience, the comparison of Jesus and Moses was not a minor theological point but a challenge to the foundational figure of Jewish identity.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The Numbers 12:7 text — "Moses was faithful in all God\'s house" — was a cornerstone of the tradition about Moses\'s unique prophetic authority. Numbers 12:6-8 establishes a hierarchy of prophetic inspiration: ordinary prophets receive visions and dreams; Moses receives direct divine speech "mouth to mouth, clearly and not in riddles." The rabbis used this passage to establish the Torah\'s unique authority — Moses\'s direct access to God gave the Mosaic Torah a directness of divine address that other prophetic texts lacked. Hebrews\' argument is that the Son exceeds even this: Moses was faithful as a servant within God\'s house, bearing witness to things that would come; the Son is over the house as its builder and heir.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Psalm 95 citation ("Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts as at Meribah") is read by Hebrews as the Holy Spirit\'s contemporary address — Scripture speaks in the present tense to the current community. This understanding of Scripture\'s present address reflects a hermeneutical principle found at Qumran: the pesher method (1QpHab, 4QpNah) reads ancient biblical texts as addressing the current community\'s situation directly ("the Teacher of Righteousness" interprets the prophets as speaking of his own community\'s experience). Hebrews shares this conviction that Scripture speaks <em>now</em> while differing in its identification of the community that is addressed.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The wilderness generation\'s rebellion is treated extensively in Second Temple Jewish literature as a negative example. Psalm 95 establishes the pattern; Numbers 14 records the specific rebellion of the spies\' report; Deuteronomy 1-3 recalls it in Moses\'s retrospective. 1 Corinthians 10:1-11 uses the same wilderness generation as a warning for the Corinthian community. The Qumran Damascus Document draws lessons from Israel\'s wilderness failures; Philo allegorizes the wilderness journey as the soul\'s moral struggle. Hebrews\' use of the wilderness generation is not unique but participates in a broad Second Temple Jewish tradition of using the Exodus narrative as a moral-theological mirror for the current community.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "1": '<p>The concept of divine "rest" (<em>anapausis</em> / <em>katapausis</em>) had theological significance in multiple streams of Second Temple Judaism. The Sabbath rest was observed as a weekly participation in God\'s creation-rest. The Promised Land was described as the place of "rest from all your enemies" (Deut 12:10; 25:19; Josh 21:44). The Temple in Jerusalem was understood as God\'s resting place (1 Chr 28:2; Ps 132:8, 14; Isa 66:1). The eschatological rest awaited after death is described in 4 Ezra 7:36 and 2 Baruch 73-74. Hebrews weaves these multiple dimensions of rest together — creation-rest, land-rest, sanctuary-rest, eschatological-rest — and argues that only the Christological fulfillment achieves what all the prior rests anticipated.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The "living and active word of God" that penetrates to the innermost human reality participates in the Jewish Wisdom tradition\'s description of divine Wisdom as pervading all things (Wis 7:22-24: "there is in her a spirit that is intelligent, holy, unique, manifold, subtle, mobile, clear, unpolluted... penetrating through all spirits that are intelligent"). Philo identifies the divine Logos with the sword of Cher Genesis 3 (On the Cherubim 35) — the flaming sword that bars Eden\'s entrance is the Logos that purifies the soul. The Qumran Rule of the Community (1QS 4:23-26) describes the Spirit of Truth as penetrating human hearts. Hebrews\' living-word passage participates in this tradition while specifically grounding it in the God-and-account relationship: the word exposes because all must give an account to God (v13).</p>',
    "14": '<p>The title "great high priest" who "has passed through the heavens" positions Jesus within the Jewish tradition of the heavenly high priest. The Epistle to the Hebrews\' view of a heavenly sanctuary in which the true high-priestly ministry occurs has antecedents in Jewish apocalyptic: 1 Enoch 14:8-23 describes the heavenly temple that Enoch visits in his vision, with its structure analogous to the earthly temple; Testament of Levi 3:4-8 describes Levi ascending to the highest heaven to receive his priestly appointment; 2 Baruch 4:3-7 describes the heavenly Jerusalem and its furnishings. In these traditions, the earthly temple is a copy of the heavenly original — the same theology that Hebrews\' Exod 25:40 citation exploits.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Herodian and Roman-period high priests were often politically appointed rather than from the legitimate Zadokite line, and their office involved compromises that scandalized many Jews. The high priest who entered the Most Holy Place on the Day of Atonement was required by Torah to have physical perfection (Lev 21:16-23); the elaborate ritual preparations (Yoma, the Talmudic tractate devoted to the Day of Atonement) included prayer-vigils, immersions, and separation from his family. The contrast with Jesus as the sinless, sympathy-capable high priest is not merely theological but addresses real anxieties in the Jewish community about whether their high priesthood was legitimate and effective.</p>'
  },
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>The Levitical high priesthood\'s structure — established at Sinai (Exod 28-29; Lev 8-9), hereditary through Aaron\'s line, with specific duties on the Day of Atonement — was the most sacred institution in Jewish religious life. The Second Temple period\'s corruption of this office created significant theological anxiety: when the Hasmoneans (not from the Aaronic priestly line but from the Levitical Hasmon family) assumed the high priesthood in 152 BCE, many Jews (including the group that became the Qumran community) considered this an illegitimate usurpation. The Teacher of Righteousness in the Dead Sea Scrolls is identified by scholars as a legitimate Zadokite high priest displaced by the Hasmonean appointment. Hebrews addresses a community that knows the high priesthood is both theologically crucial and historically corrupted.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The divine appointment of Aaron (Exod 28:1; Lev 8:1-5) was the foundational legitimation of the Levitical priesthood. The Korah rebellion (Num 16) against Moses and Aaron\'s priestly authority, and God\'s dramatic vindication of Aaron (Num 17\'s budding staff), established the principle that priestly authority was God\'s to confer, not man\'s to seize. In Second Temple Judaism, the question of legitimate priestly appointment was acute: the Hasmonean high priests claimed divine sanction for their usurpation; the Herodian high priests were political appointments. Hebrews\' argument that a legitimate priest must be divinely appointed (not self-appointing) reflects a broadly shared Jewish principle while applying it to argue that Jesus satisfies it in a way that the current Jerusalem high priesthood does not.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Gethsemane is not explicitly mentioned but the description of "loud cries and tears" to "him who was able to save him from death" is best understood as referring to Jesus\'s prayer in the garden (Mark 14:32-42; Matt 26:36-46; Luke 22:39-46). The description "with loud cries and tears" goes beyond the Gospel accounts, which record prostration and prayer but not explicit tears; the author may know an independent tradition or may be elaborating the Gethsemane tradition dramatically. The cultural context of public lamentation is relevant: in Greco-Roman and Jewish contexts, prayer accompanied by audible weeping and body-posturing was a recognized form of petition that demonstrated the seriousness of the request (cf. Elijah\'s prostration and prayer, 1 Kgs 18:42-44; Hannah\'s weeping prayer, 1 Sam 1:10-16).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The "milk vs. solid food" metaphor for levels of teaching appears in Philo of Alexandria (On the Initial Studies 19; On Agriculture 9) in the context of philosophical pedagogy: beginners receive milk (preliminary instruction); the advanced receive solid food (metaphysical and theological knowledge). The same metaphor appears in 1 Corinthians 3:1-3 for the Corinthians\' spiritual immaturity. The Qumran Rule of the Community (1QS) describes a structured process of initiation and advancement through stages of knowledge. Hebrews\' pedagogical frustration — the community should be teachers but still need teaching — reflects the expectation of spiritual progress that was standard in both Jewish and Hellenistic educational frameworks of the period.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'hebrews')
    merge_comm(existing, HEBREWS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'hebrews', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Hebrews mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
